{{Nihongo|'''''1080<U+00B0> Snowboarding'''''|<U+30C6><U+30F3><U+30FB><U+30A8><U+30A4><U+30C6><U+30A3><U+3000><U+30B9><U+30CE><U+30FC><U+30DC><U+30FC><U+30C7><U+30A3><U+30F3><U+30B0>|Ten Eiti Sun<U+014D>b<U+014D>dingu}} is a multiplayer [[snowboarding racing game|snowboard racing]] [[video game]] developed and published by [[Nintendo]] for the [[Nintendo 64]] and first released in [[Japan]] on February 22, 1998.<ref name="release">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/n64/sports/1080snowboarding/similar.html?mode=versions| publisher=[[GameSpot]]|title=1080: TenEighty Snowboarding|accessdate=2007-04-17}}</ref> The player controls one of five playable snowboarders from a [[third-person perspective]] using a combination of buttons to jump and perform tricks over eight [[Level (computer and video games)|levels]].

''1080<U+00B0>'' was announced on November 21, 1997 and developed over nine months; it garnered critical acclaim and won an Interactive Achievement Award from the [[Academy of Interactive Arts and Sciences]].<ref name="GameRankings" /><ref name="Award" /> ''1080<U+00B0>'' sold over a million units, and a second installment, ''[[1080<U+00B0> Avalanche]]'', was released for the [[Nintendo GameCube]] on November 28, 2003.

==Gameplay==
The player controls a snowboarder in one of six modes. 1080<U+00B0> has two trick modes (trick attack and contest),<ref>{{Cite book | title=1080 Snowboarding Instruction Booklet | location=Japan | publisher=Nintendo | year=1998 | pages=p.&nbsp;15<U+2013>16}}</ref> three race modes (race, time attack, and multiplayer),<ref>{{Cite book | title=1080 Snowboarding Instruction Booklet | location=Japan | publisher=Nintendo | year=1998 | pages=pp.&nbsp;12<U+2013>15,&nbsp;17}}</ref> a training mode, and an options mode.<ref>{{Cite book | title=1080 Snowboarding Instruction Booklet | location=Japan | publisher=Nintendo | year=1998 | pages=pp.&nbsp;4<U+2013>6}}</ref> The objective of the game is either to arrive quickly at a level's finish line or to receive maximum points for trick combinations.

===Trick modes===
In ''1080<U+00B0>'''s two trick modes, trick attack and contest, players accrue points from completed tricks.<ref name="All Overview">{{cite web|url=http://www.allgame.com/cg/agg.dll?p=agg&sql=1:7501~T0|title=1080<U+00B0> Snowboarding|publisher=All Game Guide|accessdate=2007-05-14}}</ref>  In contest mode, players perform tricks and snowboard past flags for points. Trick attack mode requires players to perform a series of tricks throughout a designated level. The game features 25 tricks, all of which are performed by using a combination of circular positions of the [[Nintendo 64 controller|control stick]], the R button, and the B button; point values are allocated based on complexity and required time.<ref name="All Overview" /> The two types of tricks are grab tricks, in which the board is grabbed in a specific way, or spin tricks, in which the snowboarder spins the board a certain number of degrees.<ref name="IGN rev">{{cite web |url=http://ign64.ign.com/articles/152/152225p1.html |title=1080<U+00B0> Snowboarding |accessdate=2007-04-17 |last=Casamassina |first=Matt |authorlink=Matt Casamassina |date=[[1998-04-02]] |publisher=IGN}}</ref> The 1080<U+00B0> spin requires nine actions, the most of any trick in the game.<ref name="quick ref">Operation Card for ''1080<U+00B0> Snowboarding''. Nintendo Co., Ltd. 1998.</ref>

[[Image:N64 1080.jpg|thumb|left|200px|A screenshot from a match race in ''1080<U+00B0> Snowboarding'']]

===Race modes===
''1080<U+00B0>'' has three race modes; in these modes, victory can be achieved by taking separate routes within a course and balancing the snowboarder after a jump to avoid speed loss.<ref name="GameRev" /> Tricks are scored in race modes, but do not count toward victory.<ref name="GameRev">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/n64/1080_snowboarding|title=1080 Snowboarding - N64|accessdate=2007-04-17|date=[[2004-06-06]] |publisher=Game Revolution}}</ref> 

In match race mode, the player competes in a series of races against [[Artificial intelligence|AI]]-controlled snowboarders.<ref>{{Cite book | title=1080 Snowboarding Instruction Booklet | location=Japan | publisher=Nintendo | year=1998 | pages=p.&nbsp;12}}</ref> The game times the player throughout the level and players receive a damage meter which fills if the snowboarder falls down or is knocked over. The difficulty level in match races can be set to easy, medium, or hard, adjusting the complexity and number of races. If the player fails at defeating an AI competitor, they must retire. The player is given three chances to beat the computer before the game is over.<ref name="GameRev" /><ref>{{Cite book | title=1080 Snowboarding Instruction Booklet | location=Japan | publisher=Nintendo | year=1998 | pages=pp.&nbsp;12<U+2013>13}}</ref>

===Characters===
[[Image:Characters.PNG|lright|thumb|The characters of 1080<U+00B0> from left to right: Rob Haywood, Akari Hayami, Ricky Winterborn, Kensuke Kimachi, and Dion Blaster<ref name=japan />]]
Players may initially choose from five snowboarding characters: two from Japan, and one each from Canada, America, and the United Kingdom. Each snowboarder has different abilities and is suited for different levels and modes, since each has varying statistics in fields such as technique, speed, and weight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.g4tv.com/techtvvault/features/10388/1080_Snowboarding_n64.html|title=1080 Snowboarding (n64)|date=[[1999-04-20]]|publisher=G4|accessdate=2007-05-14}}</ref><ref name="Prima Guide" /> Three additional snowboarders are unlocked by completing certain game levels and modes.<ref name="Prima Guide" /> Eight snowboards are initially available for every character, and one additional snowboard may be unlocked later in the game. Each board also excels in different situations, since each have different strengths in categories such as balance and edge control.<ref name="Prima Guide">{{cite web|url=http://guidesarchive.ign.com/guides/2225/|publisher=Prima Games|title=1080<U+00B0> Snowboarding|date=1999-12-09|accessdate=2007-06-03}}</ref>

==Development==
''1080<U+00B0>'''s release was announced on November 21, 1997 at Nintendo's [[SpaceWorld]] trade show; the game's working title was then ''Vertical Edge Snowboarding''.<ref name="Announced">{{cite web|url=http://ign64.ign.com/articles/061/061481p1.html|title=Head for the Slopes|publisher=[[IGN]]|author=IGN Staff|date=[[1997-11-21]]|accessdate=2007-05-15}}</ref> ''1080<U+00B0>'' was one of several snowboarding games released for the Nintendo 64 in 1998, others being ''[[Big Mountain 2000]]'' and ''[[Snowboard Kids]]''.<ref name="Announced" /> Before the game's release, journalists were able to play ''1080<U+00B0>'' at the January 1998 Nintendo Gamers' Summit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ign64.ign.com/articles/061/061751p1.html|title=1080 Shreds the Competition|publisher=[[IGN]]|author=IGN Staff|date=[[1998-01-30]]|accessdate=2007-05-15}}</ref>

''1080<U+00B0>'' was programmed by Englishmen Giles Goddard and Colin Reed, developed and published by [[Nintendo]], and produced by [[Shigeru Miyamoto]].<ref name="credits" /> Goddard and Reed had previously programmed ''[[Wave Race 64]]'',<ref name="tomato">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/g/nintendo_64/1080_snowboarding/overview.php|title=1080 Snowboarding |accessdate=2007-04-20|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]}}</ref> which sold over a million copies and was a huge commercial success. Its sequel, ''[[Wave Race: Blue Storm]]'', would feature characters from ''1080<U+00B0>''.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://guides.ign.com/guides/15332/page_9.html | title=Wave Race: Blue Storm Characters | last=Schneider | first=Peer | authorlink=Peer Schneider | publisher=[[IGN]] | accessdate=2007-06-03 | pages=p.&nbsp;9}}</ref>

When developing ''1080<U+00B0>'', Goddard and Reed used a technique called "skinning" to eliminate joints between the polygons composing the characters. Their programming used a combination of standard animation and [[inverse kinematics]], creating characters whose appearance during collisions is affected what object is hit, what direction the collision occurs in, and the speed at which the collision takes place.<ref name="interview" /> [[Tommy Hilfiger]] outfits and Lamar snowboards appear throughout ''1080<U+00B0>'' as [[product placement]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cheats.gamespy.com/nintendo-64/1080-snowboarding/|publisher=[[GameSpy]]|accessdate=2007-05-15|title=1080 Snowboarding (N64)}}</ref> ''1080<U+00B0>''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s soundtrack of "techno and rappy beats" with "thrashy, foozed-out vocals" was composed by [[Kenta Nagata]],<ref name="credits" /><ref name="IGN rev" /> who also composed soundtracks for ''[[Mario Kart 64]]'' and other Nintendo games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/n64/driving/mariokart64/tech_info.html|title=Mario Kart 64 Tech Info|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|accessdate=2007-05-16}}</ref>

''1080<U+00B0>'''s development took place from April or May 1997 to March 1998.<ref name="interview">{{cite web|url=http://ign64.ign.com/articles/061/061947p1.html|publisher=[[IGN]]|title=1080 Snowboarding Interview|author=IGN Staff|date=[[1998-03-19]]|accessdate=2007-04-20}}</ref> The game was released on February 28, 1998 in Japan<ref name=japan/> and on April 1, 1998 in North America.<ref name="release"/>  Nintendo delayed the game's European release because they hoped to boost sales with a winter release;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ign64.ign.com/articles/062/062006p1.html |title=1080 Delayed in Europe|publisher=[[IGN]]|author=IGN Staff|date=[[1998-03-26]]|accessdate=2007-05-15}}</ref> ''1080<U+00B0>'' was eventually released on November 30, 1998, in Europe and the [[PAL region]].<ref name="release" />

==Reception and legacy==
===Critical reception===
