Critics generally praised ''1080<U+00B0>'', which had an average score of 88/100 on [[Metacritic]] and 90% on [[Game Rankings]].<ref name="GameRankings">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/htmlpages2/196500.asp|title=1080 Snowboarding|publisher=[[Game Rankings]]|accessdate=2007-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/games/platforms/n64/1080snowboarding|title=1080<U+00B0> Snowboarding |accessdate=2007-04-17|publisher=[[Metacritic]]}}</ref> It won the [[Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences]]' 1999 Console Sports Game of the Year award<ref name="Award">{{cite web|url=http://www.interactive.org/awards.php?winners&year=1999&cat=199925#199925|title=Console Sports Game of the Year|publisher=Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences|accessdate=2007-04-23}}</ref> and was called "one of the best values in both sports and racing gaming" by Gamespot.<ref name="GameSpot review" /> ''1080<U+00B0>'' has been perceived to be a leader among snowboarding titles at the time since it was "so good...that it took publishing giant [[Electronic Arts]] several years and a far more powerful console to give it solid competition" in the form of the ''[[SSX (series)|SSX]]'' franchise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cube.ign.com/articles/442/442561p1.html|title=1080: Avalanche|publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=2007-05-16|last=Casamassina|first=Matt|date=[[2003-12-01]]}}</ref> ''[[Edge]]'' hailed it as the "most convincing videogame emulation of the snowboarding experience so far" with an "atmosphere of sobriety" unlike any other Nintendo game at the time.<ref name="Edge Review" /> 

The game's graphics were of the highest quality for the [[Nintendo 64]] at the time.<ref name="Edge Review">{{Citation|title =1080<U+00B0> Snowboarding |periodical=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]] |publisher = [[Future Publishing]]|pages = pp.&nbsp;86<U+2013>88|date = April 1998 | issue=57}}</ref><ref name="CVG" /> Critics praised general aspects of the game's graphics such as their crispness, detail, smoothness, and lack of polygon dropout.<ref name="Gamebits"/><ref name="GameSpot review">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/n64/sports/1080snowboarding/review.html |title=1080:TenEighty Snowboarding |accessdate=2007-04-17 |last=Smith |first=Josh |date=[[1998-05-25]] |publisher=[[GameSpot]]}}</ref> More specifically, critics praised the game's camera use, the game's "very solid" physics model,<ref name="GameSpot review" /> the impression of racers' speed, and the game's snow effects (sun reflected in the snow as appropriate, and fluffy snow and packed snow appeared and behaved differently).<ref name="IGN rev" /><ref name="Gamebits">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamebits.net/n64/teneight/ |title=1080 SNOWBOARDING |accessdate=2007-04-17 |last=Gagne |first=Ken  |date=[[1998-05-11]] |publisher=Gamebits}}</ref>  Graphical faults identified by critics included occasional pop-up, misplaced shadows, and lag when racers passed through on-track trees;<ref name="IGN rev" /> these problems were generally identified as minor.<ref name="GameSpot review" /> 

Although writing a positive review, ''Edge'' found faults in the game's AI; they asserted ''1080<U+00B0>'' suffered from <U+201C>cheating<U+201D> CPU opponents.<ref name="Edge Review" /> They criticized the AI's simplicity and ability to quickly catch up to the player near the end of a race; they also noted the AI's "limited series of predetermined routes" and the possibility of a player learning where and when an AI falls over, "offering an opportunity to pass [the computer], but conveying little satisfaction with it."<ref name="Edge Review" /> ''Edge'' also stated that the PAL release delay "is frankly ludicrous."<ref name="PAL Edge Review"> {{Citation |title =1080<U+00B0> Snowboarding |periodical=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]] |publisher = [[Future Publishing]]|pages = p.&nbsp;96|date = September 1998 | issue=62}}</ref> They believed that, due to Nintendo's slump of noteworthy releases, "any quality title is likely to top the charts with little difficulty."<ref name="PAL Edge Review" />

[[Allgame]] considered the "highly technical" control scheme of ''1080<U+00B0>'' one of the game's strengths despite its initial difficulty.<ref name="All Game Rev">{{cite web |url=http://www.allgame.com/cg/agg.dll?p=agg&sql=1:7501~T1 |title=1080<U+00B0> Snowboarding |accessdate=2007-04-17|last=Sackenheim |first=Shawn |publisher=[[Allgame]]}}</ref> ''[[Computer and Video Games|CVG]]'' positively reviewed the control scheme, but disagreed on its difficulty, noting "the controls have been implemented so brilliantly that you're able to play perfectly well with just one hand on the stick and Z button."<ref name="CVG">{{cite web|url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=8317|title=1080 Snowboarding|date=2001-08-15|first=Alex|last=Constantides| accessdate=2007-12-26|publisher=Computer and Video Games}}</ref> GameSpot called the game's control "thoroughly involving" and said that "[t]he crouch move alone - which makes for supertight turns - makes this fun to play."<ref name="GameSpot review" />  The music was also generally praised, with IGN calling it "a shining example of what can be achieved on the format"<ref name="IGN rev" /> and Allgame calling it "one of the best N64 soundtracks to date."<ref name="All Game Rev" /> ''Gamebits'', however, criticized the soundtrack as "minimal" and insufficient.<ref name="Gamebits" /> ''1080<U+00B0>'''s sound effects were critically praised as "some perfect sound effects" and "nice as well."<ref name="All Game Rev" /><ref name="Gamebits" />
[[Image:1080 trophy.PNG|thumb|The 1080<U+00B0> Snowboarding trophy in [[Super Smash Bros Melee]]]]
In a retrospective review by the ''[[Official Nintendo Magazine]]'' in 2006, Steve Jarratt commented that ''1080<U+00B0>'' "boasted the best videogame representation of snow," and was complimented by "swooshy" sound effects."<ref name="retrospective" >{{cite news |last=Jarratt |first=Steve |year=2006 |month=May |work=Official Nintendo Magazine||title=What do you mean, you've never played 1080<U+00B0> Snowboarding|pages=19 |accessdate=2007-12-03}}</ref> Positive comments were also made about handling and the quality of the multiplayer, despite its age.<ref name="retrospective" /> In summary, Jarratt believed "this was a straight-up snowboarder, stunt-free but fast and fun."

===Sales and legacy===
''1080<U+00B0>'' sold 1,230,000&nbsp;units in total,<ref name="magicbox">{{cite web |url=http://www.the-magicbox.com/Chart-USPlatinum.shtml |title=US Platinum Videogame Chart |accessdate=2007-04-17 |publisher=The Magic Box}}</ref> with over 23,000 in Japan.<ref name="japansales">{{cite web|url=http://www.japan-gamecharts.com/n64.php|title=Nintendo 64 Japanese Ranking|publisher=Japan Game Charts|accessdate=2007-11-13}}</ref> However, its programmers' first game, ''[[Wave Race 64]]'', sold 1,950,000&nbsp;units in total with 154,000 in Japan.<ref name="magicbox"/><ref name="japansales" /> In 2001, one of ''1080<U+00B0>'''s snowboarders, Kensuke Kimachi, appeared on a trophy in the game ''[[Super Smash Bros. Melee]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://smashbros.planets.gamespy.com/game_ssbm_troph_text.php|title=Text List|work=Super Smash Bros Arena|publisher=Gamespy|accessdate=2008-01-01}}</ref> ''[[1080<U+00B0> Avalanche]]'', a sequel to ''1080<U+00B0>'', was released for the [[Nintendo GameCube]] in 2003; ''Avalanche'' received a harsher critical reception, averaging 73/100 on [[Metacritic]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/games/platforms/gamecube/1080avalanche/|title=1080<U+00B0> Avalanche|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=2007-04-17}}</ref> due to "frame rate issues and limited gameplay".<ref name="Gamespot Ava">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/gamecube/sports/1080avalanche/review.html?page=2 |title=1080 Avalanche|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|first=Greg|last=Kasavin|authorlink=Greg Kasavin|date=[[2003-12-03]]|accessdate=2007-04-17}}</ref>  ''1080<U+00B0>'' was re-released on Nintendo's [[Virtual Console]] service in Japan on January 15, 2008, Europe on January 18, 2008 and North America on January 28, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendo.co.jp/wii/vc/lineup.html|title=Virtual Console|publisher=Nintendo|accessdate=2008-01-12}}</ref>
